From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] drivers/ps4: v18 - ICC STATUS register diagnostics

v17 reverted (pci_irq_vector returned -EINVAL because our per-device
MSI domain bypasses standard msi_get_virq lookup -- with fallback
returned virq 0 instead of working virq 3).

v18 is pure diagnostic to determine why ICC commands time out:

  1. icc_interrupt entry log (rate-limited): tells us if the IRQ
     is actually firing.  If it never fires, the issue is upstream
     (southbridge MSI generation or routing).

  2. After-init register dump: shows the static state of ICC STATUS,
     IRQ_MASK, and the actual virq we registered against.

  3. On every ICC timeout: dumps STATUS, IRQ_MASK, and REQ/REPLY
     EMPTY/FULL bits.  If STATUS has SEND/ACK bits set, the
     southbridge IS completing requests but IRQ delivery is broken.
     If REPLY full=1, the data was written but we missed the
     notification.  If STATUS=0 and REPLY empty/full unchanged from
     init, the southbridge might not even be processing requests.

Background: in v16 boot log we observed "Turn ON BT/WLAN: ret=-110,
reply 88 3c 15 40" -- non-zero data was in the reply buffer, but
icc_interrupt never woke the wait queue.  Either:
  (a) IRQ fired but our handler saw STATUS=0 (returned IRQ_NONE)
  (b) IRQ never fired (mailbox completes silently)
  (c) Reply data is leftover from PS4 OS pre-kexec, and southbridge
      isn't actually processing our requests at all

Diagnostics will distinguish these.

---
--- a/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie-icc.c
+++ b/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie-icc.c
@@ -151,6 +151,11 @@
 	u32 status;
 	u32 ret = IRQ_NONE;
 
+	/* v18 diag: log every entry so we know if IRQ ever fires */
+	pr_info_ratelimited("icc_interrupt: irq=%d entry status=0x%x\n",
+			    irq,
+			    ioread32(sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_STATUS));
+
 	do {
 		status = ioread32(sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_STATUS);
 
@@ -234,9 +239,18 @@
 	spin_lock_irq(&sc->icc.reply_lock);
 	sc->icc.reply_buffer = NULL;
 	if (ret < 0 || sc->icc.reply_pending) { /* interrupted or timed out */
+		u32 t_status, t_irqmask, t_rep_empty, t_rep_full, t_req_empty, t_req_full;
+		t_status   = ioread32(sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_STATUS);
+		t_irqmask  = ioread32(sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_IRQ_MASK);
+		t_rep_empty = ioread32(REPLY + BUF_EMPTY);
+		t_rep_full  = ioread32(REPLY + BUF_FULL);
+		t_req_empty = ioread32(REQUEST + BUF_EMPTY);
+		t_req_full  = ioread32(REQUEST + BUF_FULL);
 		sc->icc.reply_pending = false;
 		spin_unlock_irq(&sc->icc.reply_lock);
 		sc_err("icc: interrupted or timeout: ret = %d\n", ret);
+		sc_err("icc: timeout-diag STATUS=0x%x IRQ_MASK=0x%x REQ(empty=%d full=%d) REPLY(empty=%d full=%d)\n",
+		       t_status, t_irqmask, t_req_empty, t_req_full, t_rep_empty, t_rep_full);
 		return ret < 0 ? -EINTR : -ETIMEDOUT;
 	}
 	spin_unlock_irq(&sc->icc.reply_lock);
@@ -546,6 +560,13 @@
 		  sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_IRQ_MASK);
 	mutex_unlock(&bcpie_icc_mutex);
 
+	/* v18 diag: dump initial register state after enabling IRQs */
+	sc_info("icc init-diag: ICC virq=%d STATUS=0x%x IRQ_MASK=0x%x DOORBELL_off=0x%x STATUS_off=0x%x\n",
+		bpcie_irqnum(sc, BPCIE_SUBFUNC_ICC),
+		ioread32(sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_STATUS),
+		ioread32(sc->bar2 + BPCIE_REG_ICC_IRQ_MASK),
+		BPCIE_REG_ICC_DOORBELL, BPCIE_REG_ICC_STATUS);
+
 	ret = icc_i2c_init(sc);
 	if (ret) {
 		sc_err("icc: i2c init failed: %d\n", ret);
